'''Periodic fever, aphthous stomatitis, pharyngitis and adenitis''' or '''periodic fever aphthous pharyngitis and cervical adenopathy''' (PFAPA) syndrome is a medical condition, typically starting in young children, in which high [[fever]] occurs periodically at intervals of about 3–5 weeks, frequently accompanied by [[aphthous ulcer]]s, [[pharyngitis]] and/or [[Cervical lymph nodes|cervical]] [[adenitis]]. The syndrome was described in 1987 and named two years later.<ref name="ThomasPFAPA">{{cite journal
